  "learnings_before": "- Valproate (syrup, tablet or dispersible) is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies, costs ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg dose, and is the preferred first‑line AED for children ≤ 2 years with focal or generalized seizures unless a contraindication is documented.  \n- Recommended therapeutic range for valproate is 20–30 mg/kg/day; doses outside this window should be adjusted only after confirming a serum valproate level < 50 µg/mL and normal baseline liver enzymes (ALT/AST < 2× ULN) and platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L.  \n- If a prescription section lists a drug and dose, the default action is to continue that regimen unchanged unless the clinical notes explicitly state a dose change, adverse event, or laboratory abnormality.  \n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases when valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable or contraindicated; it is avoided in children with spastic cerebral palsy because sedation occurs in ~30 % of such patients.  \n- Clobazam is not on the Ugandan Essential Medicines List for pediatric epilepsy and is rarely stocked; it should only be used if specifically prescribed by the clinician and serum clobazam levels are available (valproate co‑administration markedly increases clobazam concentrations).  \n- Levetiracetam is an effective non‑aromatic alternative; its cost is 2–3 × that of valproate and dispersible tablets may be intermittently unavailable, so it is considered only when valproate is contraindicated, poorly tolerated, or unavailable in any formulation.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) should be avoided in any child with a prior drug‑induced rash; if a rash history exists, the regimen defaults to valproate ± levetiracetam.  \n- Adherence ≥ 80 % (based on caregiver report and pharmacy refill data) is required before adding a third agent; otherwise the strategy is to optimise dosing or simplify the existing regimen.  \n- Formulation substitution precedes any change of active drug: when syrup is unaffordable or out of stock, switch to equivalent tablets or dispersible formulation rather than selecting a different AED.  \n- Valproate inhibition of CYP enzymes can raise plasma levels of concurrent antiretrovirals and zidovudine; phenobarbital induction can reduce efficacy of antimalarials and protease‑inhibitor‑based ART, so drug‑interaction checks are mandatory when co‑prescribing.  \n- In infants < 2 years, valproate carries a higher risk of hepatotoxicity and hyperammonemia; baseline and repeat LFTs and ammonia should be obtained before initiation and after any dose increase.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjuncts: phenobarbital (cheapest, widely available) is preferred over levetiracetam when an adjunct is required and no sedation or interaction contraindications exist.  \n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window and no safety concerns are present, the recommended next step is to maintain the current valproate dose unchanged.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Carbamazepine (or phenobarbital when carbamazepine unavailable) is the recommended first‑line AED for focal seizures in children < 2 years; valproate is reserved for generalized seizures or when carbamazepine/phenobarbital are contraindicated.  \n- Therapeutic window for carbamazepine in infants is 15–20 mg/kg/day; doses up to 30 mg/kg/day are used only after documented failure at the lower range.  \n- Valproate dosing target is 20–30 mg/kg/day; in children < 2 years any dose increase is prohibited unless recent liver function tests and ammonia are normal.  \n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) must be avoided in any child with a prior drug‑induced rash or documented severe hepatic impairment.  \n- Phenobarbital is the preferred low‑cost adjunct when seizure control remains inadequate after optimal first‑line dosing and no sedation or interaction contraindications exist; add only after ≥ 2 adequately dosed first‑line agents have failed.  \n- Clobazam is the preferred adjunct for Lennox‑Gastaut syndrome; start 0.25 mg/kg BID, titrate to 1 mg/kg BID, and monitor for increased sedation due to valproate‑induced level rise.  \n- Levetiracetam is considered only when valproate is contraindicated or unavailable, or when clobazam/phenobarbital are unsuitable; cost is 2–3 × that of valproate and formulations may be intermittently out of stock.  \n- Formulation substitution (syrup ↔ tablet ↔ dispersible) must be attempted before changing the active drug; both carbamazepine and valproate are stocked in > 90 % of district pharmacies, phenobarbital in > 95 %, levetiracetam in ≤ 70 %.  \n- Default action: if no adverse event, no laboratory abnormality, and no explicit dose‑change note are recorded, continue the current regimen unchanged and terminate decision‑making.  \n- Age‑specific safety gate: for patients < 2 years, prohibit any valproate dose increase or initiation without documented normal LFTs, ammonia, and platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L.  \n- Adherence threshold: require documented caregiver adherence ≥ 80 % before adding a third agent; if adherence is uncertain, reinforce counseling and reassess rather than modify therapy.  \n- Data‑gap rule: missing liver function tests, serum drug levels, or rash history constitute a hard stop for dose escalation or drug switch; maintain current regimen and schedule necessary investigations.  \n- Cost‑effectiveness hierarchy for adjuncts (when indicated): clobazam > phenobarbital > levetiracetam > topiramate; selection follows availability, affordability, and sedation profile.  \n- Refractory status definition: consider adjunct therapy only after ≥ 3 seizures per month despite optimal dosing of ≥ 2 first‑line agents, or when seizure type changes (e.g., emergence of absence seizures in a focal epilepsy regimen).  \n- “Stay‑the‑course” fallback: when the first‑line drug is on the essential medicines list, dose lies within the accepted local therapeutic window, no safety red flags exist, and the formulation is available, continue the regimen unchanged and plan follow‑up.  \n- Gender‑specific safety note: in females ≥ 12 years, avoid valproate unless no alternative exists due to teratogenic risk.  \n- Drug‑interaction checkpoint: when phenobarbital is added to valproate, obtain a repeat valproate level after 1 week and increase valproate dose by ≈ 20 % if sub‑therapeutic; conversely, valproate co‑administration with clobazam requires starting clobazam at the lowest dose and monitoring sedation.",
